      modelAnswer: 'Cardiovascular disease (CVD) covers conditions affecting the heart and blood vessels, especially atherosclerosis — the build-up of fatty plaques in artery walls. Plaques narrow vessels, reduce blood flow, can rupture and trigger blood clots that cause heart attack or stroke. Lifestyle factors that raise risk include diet (high saturated and trans fat, high salt and refined sugar, low fibre), smoking (damages endothelium, raises blood pressure and lowers HDL), physical inactivity, obesity (especially central), excess alcohol and chronic stress. Each factor contributes to one or more underlying drivers: high LDL cholesterol, hypertension, insulin resistance, inflammation, and a tendency to clotting. Smoking, for example, raises blood pressure and damages the endothelium, allowing LDL to enter the artery wall, where it is oxidised and triggers plaque formation. A diet high in saturated fat raises serum LDL and lowers HDL, while soluble fibre and unsaturated fats improve the LDL/HDL ratio. Risk can be reduced by tackling each factor: stopping smoking gives rapid health benefits; a Mediterranean-style diet reduces CVD events (PREDIMED trial); regular aerobic exercise (~150 min/week) reduces blood pressure, weight and LDL; alcohol within recommended limits; weight loss; managing stress. Pharmacological options include statins (lower LDL), antihypertensives, and antiplatelets where indicated. Public health measures include smoking bans, salt reduction in processed foods, and clearer food labelling. Genetic factors also matter (familial hypercholesterolaemia) but most CVD is preventable through lifestyle change. Evidence comes from epidemiological studies (Seven Countries Study, INTERHEART), cohort studies and intervention trials. While no single change eliminates risk, the combined effect of multiple lifestyle changes is large, and most CVD deaths are avoidable.'
