      modelAnswer: 'The heart is a four-chambered double pump. Two thin-walled atria collect blood and pass it to two thicker-walled ventricles, which pump blood out under pressure. The right side handles deoxygenated blood and pumps it through the pulmonary circuit to the lungs at low pressure (protecting delicate alveolar capillaries); the left side pumps oxygenated blood through the systemic circuit to the rest of the body at high pressure. The left ventricle has the thickest wall to generate the necessary force. Atrioventricular valves (tricuspid right, bicuspid left) prevent backflow into atria during ventricular contraction; semi-lunar valves (pulmonary, aortic) prevent backflow into ventricles during diastole. The cardiac cycle has three phases: atrial systole (atria contract, top up ventricles); ventricular systole (ventricles contract, AV valves close, semi-lunar valves open, blood ejected); diastole (all chambers relaxed, semi-lunar valves close, atria refill from veins). Heart contraction is myogenic, coordinated by the sinoatrial (SA) node, which sets the pace. Impulses are delayed at the AV node so atria empty before ventricles contract, then conducted rapidly down the bundle of His and Purkyne fibres, producing simultaneous contraction from the apex upwards. The cardiovascular centre in the medulla adjusts heart rate via the autonomic nervous system, while adrenaline and circulating signals fine-tune output to match demand. This combination of structural specialisation and coordinated electrical activity ensures continuous, efficient flow at the right pressure to every tissue.'
