      modelAnswer: 'Cystic fibrosis (CF) is caused by mutations in the CFTR gene on chromosome 7. The most common mutation, ΔF508, deletes three bases coding for phenylalanine 508 of the CFTR protein. CFTR is a chloride ion channel in the apical membrane of epithelial cells lining airways, ducts and the gut. Normally, CFTR transports Cl⁻ out of cells; water follows by osmosis, keeping mucus thin and easy to clear. The mutated protein misfolds and is degraded before reaching the membrane; chloride transport is reduced. Without proper Cl⁻ transport, mucus on epithelial surfaces is dehydrated and becomes thick and sticky. The disease therefore affects every organ with secretory epithelium. In the lungs, thick mucus accumulates, blocking small airways, impairing ciliary clearance and providing a breeding ground for bacteria such as Pseudomonas aeruginosa; chronic infection and inflammation progressively destroy lung tissue, causing breathlessness and respiratory failure — the main cause of death. In the pancreas, sticky secretions block the ducts, preventing digestive enzymes reaching the gut and damaging the pancreas itself; this causes malabsorption (especially of fats), poor weight gain and, eventually, diabetes if islet cells are destroyed. In the liver, blocked bile ducts can cause cirrhosis. In the gut, thick mucus can cause meconium ileus in newborns and ongoing constipation. In sweat glands, faulty Cl⁻ reabsorption produces salty sweat — the basis of the diagnostic sweat test. In the reproductive tract, thick mucus blocks the vas deferens, causing infertility in most men with CF; women have reduced fertility. CF is therefore a single-gene disease with many phenotypic effects (pleiotropy), reflecting the wide expression of CFTR. Modern treatments include physiotherapy, nutritional support, antibiotics, mucolytics, and CFTR modulators such as ivacaftor and tezacaftor/elexacaftor that partly restore protein function for specific mutations, dramatically improving life expectancy.'
