      modelAnswer: 'A fertilised egg (zygote) is totipotent — it can give rise to all cell types of the organism, including extra-embryonic tissues. Cleavage divisions (mitosis without growth) produce a morula and then a blastocyst, with an inner cell mass surrounded by trophoblast. The inner cell mass is pluripotent — its cells can form any tissue but not extra-embryonic membranes. Gastrulation organises cells into three germ layers: ectoderm (becomes skin and nervous system), mesoderm (muscle, bone, blood, kidneys) and endoderm (gut lining, lungs, liver, pancreas). Cells then become multipotent (e.g. haematopoietic stem cells producing several blood cell lineages) and finally unipotent or fully differentiated. Differentiation involves stable changes in gene expression rather than gene loss: virtually all cells contain the same genome, but only a subset of genes is active in each cell type. Patterns are set by transcription factors (e.g. MyoD switches on muscle genes), epigenetic marks (DNA methylation, histone modifications) that lock down inactive genes, and cell-cell signalling (Notch, Wnt, Hedgehog pathways) that guides cells based on their position. Morphogen gradients (e.g. Sonic hedgehog along the embryo axis) provide positional information; cells respond differently to different concentrations. Apoptosis sculpts tissues by removing unwanted cells (e.g. between fingers in development). Asymmetric cell division produces daughter cells with different fates. The same fundamental processes — selective gene expression, cell signalling and programmed cell death — generate the enormous variety of cell types from one starting cell. Stem cells in adult tissues continue to differentiate throughout life to replace lost cells. Misregulation of these processes underlies developmental abnormalities and cancer, demonstrating how powerfully the genome shapes phenotype through controlled gene expression.'
