      modelAnswer: 'Biodiversity is the variety of life at species, genetic and ecosystem levels. Measurement methods include species richness (number of species in an area), Simpson\'s and Shannon-Wiener diversity indices (which take account of relative abundance, giving more weight to evenness), genetic diversity (allele frequencies, heterozygosity, sequencing) and ecosystem diversity (variety of habitats and ecological processes). Sampling techniques include quadrats and transects for plants and slow-moving animals, mark-release-recapture for mobile animals, and DNA metabarcoding of environmental samples for microbes. Each method has limitations: species lists miss cryptic species and relative abundance, diversity indices depend on taxonomic resolution, and large mobile species need different approaches than small soil organisms. Biodiversity matters ecologically because diverse ecosystems are generally more stable and productive: different species occupy different niches, redundancy means functions can be maintained if one species declines, and complex food webs absorb perturbations better than simple ones. Diverse pollinator communities maintain crop yields; diverse soil microbes drive nutrient cycling; diverse forests sequester more carbon. Economically, biodiversity provides direct goods (timber, fish, food) and ecosystem services (pollination, water purification, flood control, climate regulation) worth trillions of pounds per year. Genetically diverse species are a resource for crop and livestock improvement; many medicines (penicillin from a fungus, taxol from yew trees, statins from a fungus) come from wild species. Culturally and ethically, biodiversity has intrinsic value, recreational, aesthetic and spiritual significance, and we have responsibility to future generations. Threats include habitat loss, climate change, pollution, invasive species and overexploitation; current extinction rates are 100–1000 times background, and the IPBES report warns of mass biodiversity loss. Conservation through protected areas, sustainable use, restoration and tackling underlying drivers (climate, agriculture) is therefore both ecologically necessary and economically and ethically justified.'
