      modelAnswer: 'Sustainable conservation aims to maintain biodiversity and ecosystem function without depleting natural resources for future generations. Approaches include in situ methods (within natural habitats) and ex situ methods (outside). In situ approaches include national parks and nature reserves, where protection of habitat allows whole ecosystems to function; marine protected areas; restoration of degraded habitats (reforestation, wetland restoration); and legal frameworks such as CITES, which restricts trade in endangered species, and the Convention on Biological Diversity. These maintain natural genetic diversity and ecological interactions but require enforcement and may conflict with local livelihoods. Ex situ approaches include zoos, botanic gardens, captive breeding programmes and seed banks. Captive breeding has saved species like the California condor and Arabian oryx from extinction and allowed reintroduction, but can suffer from inbreeding, behavioural changes and lack of habitat to return to. Seed banks (Kew\'s Millennium Seed Bank, Svalbard Global Seed Vault) preserve genetic diversity cheaply for hundreds of years. Sustainable use ties human livelihoods to conservation: certified sustainable forestry (FSC), sustainable fisheries (MSC), ecotourism, community-based natural resource management. Best results come from combining approaches: protected areas core, sustainable use buffers, and restoration of corridors connecting fragmented habitats. Effectiveness varies. Protected areas have slowed but not halted biodiversity loss; many are "paper parks" without enforcement. Captive breeding is effective for charismatic species but costly per species saved. Sustainable use can succeed where local communities benefit, but is hard to enforce globally. Climate change increasingly undermines conservation by shifting habitats. Genuine sustainability requires tackling underlying drivers (population growth, consumption, climate change) and recognising that conservation is also about people. Ecosystem services valuation is reshaping policy by giving conservation an economic case. While none of these approaches is sufficient alone, a combination tailored to context — and supported by governance, funding and equity — offers the best chance of conserving biodiversity for the long term.'
