      modelAnswer: 'Climate change driven by anthropogenic CO₂, methane and other greenhouse-gas emissions is producing higher mean temperatures, altered rainfall, sea-level rise, more extreme weather and ocean acidification. Effects on ecosystems are wide-ranging. Distributions shift — species move polewards or to higher altitudes as temperatures rise — but specialists and slow-moving species may be unable to keep pace. Phenology changes — bud burst, flowering, breeding and migration timings shift — leading to mismatches between, e.g., predator and prey or pollinator and plant. Coral reefs are bleached as warm water expels symbiotic algae; ocean acidification reduces calcification. Polar habitats lose ice, threatening polar bears, walrus, krill-dependent food webs. Tropical forests face droughts and fires; temperate forests are stressed by pests and storms. Migration corridors disappear, raising extinction risks. Knock-on effects include altered nutrient cycles, biome boundaries and disease patterns (vectors expand range). Mitigation aims to reduce emissions: switching to renewable energy (solar, wind, hydro, nuclear), increasing energy efficiency, electrifying transport, halting deforestation, reforestation, soil-carbon management, reducing meat consumption and developing carbon capture and storage. International agreements (Paris) set targets but national ambition varies. Adaptation accepts some change is unavoidable: planning for sea-level rise (managed retreat, coastal defences), drought-resistant crops, ecosystem-based adaptation (mangrove restoration), assisted migration of vulnerable species, and protecting climate refugia. Conservation strategies must be dynamic: new protected areas anticipating shifted ranges; corridors connecting fragmented habitats; assisted gene flow; ex situ insurance populations and seed banks. Effectiveness depends on speed and ambition: limiting warming to 1.5–2 °C reduces but does not eliminate ecosystem damage, while higher warming drives mass extinction risks. Equity matters — poorer countries and populations bear most cost despite lowest emissions. Mitigation reduces the future scale of change while adaptation manages what is unavoidable; both must be pursued together. Without rapid emissions cuts, no amount of adaptation will preserve ecosystems as we know them, but combined urgent action across all fronts can still preserve much biodiversity for future generations.'
